---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Alienation as Coercive Control — Domestic Abuse by Another Name"
  description="How parental alienation fits the Duluth Model of domestic violence. The Power and Control Wheel mapped to alienation, and why this reframing changes everything."
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="section section-dark-light hero-section">
    <div class="container-narrow" style="text-align:center;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Part I — The Alienating Parent</p>
      <h1>Alienation as Coercive Control</h1>
      <p class="hero-intro">
        Parental alienation is not a custody dispute that got out of hand. It is
        a system of coercive control — executed relationally, sustained over time,
        and carried out through the child. Understanding this reframing changes
        everything: legally, clinically, and personally.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The reframing -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>The domestic abuse framework</h2>
      <p class="lead-text">
        A common misunderstanding is that alienation is "just a custody issue" or a
        messy divorce. But modern research — particularly the work of Dr Jennifer
        Harman — has reframed parental alienation as a form of family violence and
        coercive control. Alienation co-occurs with intimate partner violence in
        approximately 50% of cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not a metaphor. The mechanisms are identical. The alienating parent
        uses the same toolkit of control, isolation, intimidation, and emotional
        manipulation that characterises other forms of domestic abuse — but the
        weapon is the child, and the abuse continues long after the relationship
        has ended.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Power and Control Wheel -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>The Power and Control Wheel</h2>
      <p>
        The Duluth Model's Power and Control Wheel — the standard framework for
        understanding domestic abuse — maps directly onto alienation dynamics.
        Each spoke of the wheel has a corresponding alienation behaviour.
      </p>

      <div class="wheel-grid">
        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Emotional abuse</h3>
          <p>
            Badmouthing, name-calling, humiliation of the targeted parent — both
            directly to the child and through the child. Making the child feel
            that loving you is shameful.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Intimidation</h3>
          <p>
            Creating fear through angry outbursts, threats, or emotionally charged
            reactions when the child shows affection toward you. The child learns
            that positive feelings about you are dangerous.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Isolation</h3>
          <p>
            Limiting contact, blocking communication, severing ties with your
            extended family. Controlling who the child sees, speaks to, and
            receives information from. Creating a closed information system.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Minimising, denying, blaming</h3>
          <p>
            "I never said anything bad about their father." "The child just
            doesn't want to go — I can't force them." "If he were a better parent,
            the child wouldn't feel this way." The alienator denies the behaviour,
            minimises its impact, and blames you for the outcome.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Using children</h3>
          <p>
            The defining feature of alienation. The child is used as a messenger,
            a spy, a weapon, and a source of validation. Their emotional wellbeing
            is subordinated to the alienator's need for control.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Entitlement and privilege</h3>
          <p>
            Acting as the "real" parent, the gatekeeper, the final authority.
            Treating access to the child as a privilege they grant rather than
            a right the child has. "I decide what is best for my child."
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Economic control</h3>
          <p>
            Using financial leverage — withholding child support information,
            exhausting your resources through litigation, making the child
            financially dependent on one household. The "golden handcuffs."
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="wheel-card card">
          <h3>Coercion and threats</h3>
          <p>
            Threatening to restrict access, file false reports, or move away
            with the child. Using the legal system as a weapon. Creating an
            environment where compliance — your silence, your retreat — is the
            price of any contact at all.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The diagnostic bridge -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>The diagnostic bridge</h2>
      <p>
        What makes this framework so powerful is that it creates a bridge between
        two fields that have historically operated in isolation: domestic violence
        research and parental alienation research. Gardner's eight behavioural
        manifestations — the child's symptoms — map directly onto the Power and
        Control Wheel — the alienator's methods.
      </p>
      <p>
        The child's "independent" rejection is not independent at all. It is the
        internalised script of the parent's coercive control. The child who says
        "I hate you and it's all my own idea" is displaying the same pattern as
        any victim who has absorbed their abuser's worldview and defends it as
        their own.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-box">
        <p class="callout-label">Why this matters legally</p>
        <p>
          In jurisdictions that recognise coercive control as a criminal offence,
          framing alienation within this framework opens legal avenues that pure
          "custody dispute" language does not. It shifts the conversation from
          "two parents who can't agree" to "one parent who is systematically
          controlling and abusing the other through the child."
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Post-separation abuse -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>Post-separation abuse</h2>
      <p>
        One of the most important insights from the coercive control framework is
        that the abuse does not stop when the relationship ends. For many targeted
        parents, the separation is not the end of the control — it is the
        beginning of a new form of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The alienating parent cannot control you directly anymore. So they control
        you through the child. Every cancelled visit, every blocked phone call,
        every false allegation, every court application is an act of continued
        control — executed at a distance, through institutions, and through the
        person you love most.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why so many targeted parents describe feeling more controlled
        <em>after</em> the separation than during the relationship. The mechanism
        has changed. The dynamic has not.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="pull-quote">
        "Parental alienation is not a conflict gone wrong. It is a system of
        coercive control — executed relationally, sustained over time, and
        carried out through the child."
      </blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-dark" style="text-align:center;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
      <p style="opacity:0.85; margin-bottom:2rem; max-width:580px; margin-inline:auto;">
        Coercive control is rarely a solo act. The next page explores the network
        of enablers that sustains the alienation campaign.
      </p>
      <div class="next-links">
        <a href="/understanding/the-alienating-parent/the-enablers" class="btn btn-primary">The Enablers</a>
        <a href="/understanding/the-alienating-parent" class="btn btn-outline-light">Back to The Alienating Parent</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

